<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880706-0134 </DOCNO><HL> REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides: The Criminal P/E </HL><SO> </SO><G> JUS </G><TEXT>   The National Institute of Justice reports that prisons are about the best investment taxpayers can make. A study of three states by this Justice Department agency found that it cost $25,000 a year to keep prisoners under key. Compare this with the average $430,000 each prisoner on the street causes each year with 187 crimes in victim losses, law-enforcement costs and private security expenditures. </TEXT></DOC>